		<description></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>A custom block to showcase a bio box for WordPress users. This was a coding challenge sent to me around June of 2022, which was quite literally impossible - but I'll explain the workarounds that I figured out, what works and what doesn't.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:heading {"level":3} -->
<h3>Limitations</h3>
<!-- /wp:heading -->

<!-- wp:list -->
<ul><li>The WordPress REST API Users Endpoint will only allow users with the role of Administrator, or properly authenticated users, to pull all data for all users of the website. This is a security limitation, with the understanding that email addresses are sacred, should not really be publicly accessible, but as an Admin you should be able to access them. </li><li>The WordPress REST API Users Endpoint does not allow (out of the box) access to the users' email addresses. I asked in the Make WordPress Slack why this was, and the answer I received from a core contributor was as follows: </li></ul>
<!-- /wp:list -->

<!-- wp:quote -->
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote"><p>Of course, but then again, each situation is different. Not exposing user email addresses is general good practice, but like I said in the thread, exposure may only be for authenticated users with a certain permission, or with a token that authorizes an app to access that information. Exposing it in that way doesn't make the email address public</p><cite>@costdev on Making WordPress Slack</cite></blockquote>
<!-- /wp:quote -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>The magic behind allowing access to this data in the endpoint is below: </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:syntaxhighlighter/code {"language":"php"} -->
<pre class="wp-block-syntaxhighlighter-code">&lt;?php 
// Expose email in REST API users endpoint
	register_rest_field( 'user', 'user_email',
	array(
	'get_callback'    => function ( $user ) {
		return get_userdata($user['id'])->user_email;
	},
	'update_callback' => null,
	'schema'          => null,
	)</pre>
<!-- /wp:syntaxhighlighter/code -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>There is no documentation about this in the REST API docs, I had to play around with the `user_email` variable <em>name</em> to get the correct <em>value</em> returned, finally figuring out that is what it was called, because it's not returned by default from the API.  </p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->]]></content:encoded>
